{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161214173439|754814981","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Bob_Dold","to":"Bob Dold"}],"pages":{"26100557":{"pageid":26100557,"ns":0,"title":"Bob Dold","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-24T18:41:32Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{distinguish|Bob Dole}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Robert Dold\n|image       = Robert Dold official portrait 114th Congress.jpg\n|state       = [[Illinois]]\n|district    = {{ushr|Illinois|10|10th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Brad Schneider]]\n|successor    = [[Brad Schneider]] (Elect)\n|term_start1  = January 3, 2011\n|term_end1    = January 3, 2013\n|predecessor1 = [[Mark Kirk]]\n|successor1   = [[Brad Schneider]]\n|birthname   = Robert James Dold, Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|6|23}}\n|birth_place = [[Evanston, Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|residence= [[Kenilworth, Illinois]]\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Danielle Dold\n|children    = 3\n|alma_mater  = [[Denison University]]<br>{{nowrap|[[Indiana University]]}}<br>[[Kellogg School of Management|Northwestern University]]\n|religion    = [[Christianity]]\n|website     = [http://www.doldforcongress.com/ Campaign website]<br>[https://dold.house.gov/ Official website]\n}}\n'''Robert James \"Bob\" Dold, Jr.'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legistorm.com/memberbio/2748/Rep_Robert_Dold_IL.html |title=Representative Robert James Dold (Robert) (R-Illinois, 10th) \u2013 Biography from |publisher=LegiStorm |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> (born June 23, 1969) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|IL|10}}, having served since 2015. He previously served from 2011 to 2013. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Seals concedes congressional race in 10th District | publisher = [[ABC News]] | date=3 November 2010 | accessdate=2010-11-03 | url=http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=7762723}}</ref> Prior to his election, Dold ran his family-owned business, Rose Pest Solutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rosepestcontrol.com/ |title=Rose Pest Solutions |publisher=Rosepestcontrol.com |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> <!-- Not to be confused with a similar company with the same name:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rosepestsolutions.com/|title=Rose Pest Solutions|publisher=|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> --> In 2010, Dold defeated Democratic Party nominee [[Dan Seals (Illinois politician)|Dan Seals]] to replace Republican incumbent [[Mark Kirk]] in the U.S. House of Representatives. Dold was narrowly defeated by Democrat [[Brad Schneider]] in 2012, but regained the seat in 2014, defeating Schneider in a rematch. He was again defeated by Schneider in 2016 in a third contest between the two.\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\n\nDold was born in [[Evanston, Illinois]], the son of Judith Gail (n\u00e9e Kelley) and Robert James Dold. His ancestry includes German, Swedish, Irish, Scottish, and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/dold.htm |title=Bob Dold ancestry |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref> He graduated from New Trier High School where he was quarterback of the football team and captain of the wrestling and lacrosse teams.<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet Bob|url=http://doldforcongress.com/about/|website=Dold for Congress|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] degree from [[Denison University]] where he served as President of the Campus Governance Association and acted as a member of [[Beta Theta Pi]], a [[Juris Doctor|JD]] degree from [[Indiana University]] where he was selected by his classmates to give the commencement address, and an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] degree from [[Northwestern University]]\u2019s [[Kellogg School of Management]].<ref>[https://www.gop.com/leaders/congressman-bob-dold-il Congressman Bob Dold] - website of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]</ref>\n\nDold was an intern in the administration of Vice President [[Dan Quayle]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stiefel|first1=Lynne|title=Former veep weighs in|url=http://blogs.pioneerlocal.com/northshore/2010/01/quayle-on-obama.html|accessdate=9 September 2014|publisher=Pioneer Local|date=20 January 2010}}</ref> He also clerked for a New York State Judge and served as an investigative counsel for the Republican-led [[House Government Reform Committee|House Government Reform and Oversight Committee]].<ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-12D192F78ED58028.html Small businessman's roots run deep in district], Lynn Stiefel, ''[[Pioneer Press]]'', January 7, 2010</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2010#District 10}}\nIn his first radio ad of the general election campaign, Dold described himself as a small business owner, fiscal conservative, and social moderate.<ref>[http://www.chicagogop.com/home/dold-launches-first-radio-ad.html Dold Launches First Radio Ad], Dold for Congress Press Release, Chicago GOP, July 21, 2010. Retrieved August 18, 2010.</ref> Dold was endorsed by the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=For the US House|date=7 October 2010|accessdate=2010-10-08|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-edit-congress-20101007,0,587673.story?page=1}}</ref> whose editorial page editor, R. Bruce Dold, is not related to Bob Dold.<ref>{{cite news|title=Come on, Mr. Seals|date=25 October 2010|accessdate=2016-01-15|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-10-25/opinion/ct-edit-seals-20101025_1_dold-and-seals-republican-robert-dold-abortion-rights}}</ref> The [[United States Chamber of Commerce|US Chamber of Commerce]]<ref name=\"pioneer\">[http://www.pioneerlocal.com/glenview/news/2704246,glenview-10thbriefs-091610-s1.article], ''[[Pioneer Press]]'', Sept. 13, 2010 {{dead link|date=March 2012}}</ref> and the Electrical Contractors' Association<ref name=\"newssunjuly\">[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:21t4W4BC_KUJ:poll.suburbanchicagonews.com/newssun/news/2512508,5_1_WA20_POLBRFS_S1-100720.article Political Briefs], ''[[Lake County News-Sun]]'', July 20, 2010</ref> also endorsed him. Former New York City mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]]<ref name=\"pioneer\"/> and president of [[Americans for Tax Reform]] [[Grover Norquist]]<ref>[http://thecapitolfaxblog.com/2010/09/20/new-ads-by-foster-nrcc-norquist-endorses-dold-nazi-smear/ New ads by Foster, NRCC; Norquist endorses Dold; Nazi smear], Rich Miller, ''The Capitol Fax Blog'', September 20, 2010</ref> campaigned for Dold. After reporting nearly equal fund-raising for the second quarter,<ref>[http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2010/07/dold_seals_tied_in_second_quar.html Dold, Seals tied in second quarter fund-raising in Illinois 10th House district], Lynn Sweet, ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', July 15, 2010</ref> Dold's fund-raising outpaced Seals' in the third quarter. Dold began the final quarter with more cash on hand than Seals.<ref>{{cite web | author = Lynne Stiefel | title = 10th Congress District: Show me the money |work=[[Pioneer Press]] | date = 18 October 2010 | accessdate = 2010-10-18 | url = http://www.pioneerlocal.com/wilmette/news/2812556,glenview-10thfin-102110-s1.article}}</ref> At the request of the [[Federal Election Commission]], the Dold campaign amended its second quarter filing in September 2010 to reflect debts and expenditures that had been incurred in the second quarter but had not yet been billed when the filing period ended.<ref>[http://www.wgntv.com/news/wgntv-bob-dold-fed-investigation-sept30,0,4572973.story Candidate's campaign finance called into question FEC looking into Republican Bob Dold's campaign funds], Randi Belisomo, [[WGN-TV|WGN News]], September 30, 2010 {{dead link|date=September 2014}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2012#District 10}}\nThe ''[[National Journal]]'''s [[Cook Political Report]] named Dold one of the top 10 Republicans most vulnerable to redistricting in 2012<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nationaljournal.com/top-10-republicans-most-vulnerable-to-redistricting-20110415|title= Top 10 Republicans Most Vulnerable to Redistricting  |author= David Wasserman and Julia Edwards|date= April 15, 2011|work= Cook Political Report|publisher= National Journal|accessdate=April 25, 2011}}</ref> with the 10th becoming more Democratic following redistricting. The endorsement of Mark Kirk, who was popular in the district at the time, was expected to help Dold.<ref name=\"nbcchicago1\">{{cite web|last=McClelland |first=Edward |url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/Ward-Room-Handicaps-The-Congressional-Races-143978246.html |title=Handicapping The Congressional Races |publisher=NBC Chicago |date=March 23, 2012 |accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> Dold had a strong cash-on-hand advantage over his opponent [[Brad Schneider]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Lissau|first=Russell|title=Sheyman, Schneider lead Democratic candidates in 10th District cash race|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20120202/news/702029882/|newspaper=Daily Herald|date=February 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sheyman Brings a 'Truly Progressive Voice'|url=http://buffalogrove.patch.com/articles/sheyman-brings-a-truly-progressive-voice|newspaper=Buffalo Grove Patch|date=March 7, 2012}}</ref> Dold earned the endorsement of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' and ''[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-edit-intro-1007-20121007,0,4787522.story | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Searching for solutions | date=October 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20121009/discuss/710099946/|title=Endorsement: Dold over Schneider in 10th Congressional District|work=Daily Herald|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> Schneider defeated Dold 51%\u201349%, a difference of just 3,000 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/IL|title=2014 Election Results Senate: Map by State, Live Midterm Voting Updates|work=POLITICO|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2014#District 10}}\nOn May 8, 2013, Dold announced in an e-mail to supporters that he would run for his old seat in 2014.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-05-09/news/ct-met-bob-dold-rematch-0509-20130509_1_brad-schneider-outside-spending-10th-district | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Dold out to reclaim north suburban congressional seat | date=May 9, 2013}}</ref> He was actively recruited to run again.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lester|first1=Kerry|title=Dold being recruited by top GOP to run again in 10th|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20130415/news/704159797/|accessdate=9 September 2014|publisher=Daily Herald|date=15 April 2013}}</ref> The race was ranked the #7 most likely flip for 2014 House rematches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/ranking_potential_flips_for_2014_house_rematches-224563-1.html?pg=2|title=Ranking Potential Flips for 2014 House Rematches|work=Roll Call|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> Dold won the rematch by slightly more than 4,800 votes and took office at the start of the 114th Congress.\n\n;2016\n{{main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois, 2016#District 10}}\n\nDold ran for re-election in 2016. He faced a rematch with Democrat [[Brad Schneider]] in the general election. Dold was defeated by Schneider, who received 53% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Skiba|first1=Katherine|title=Schneider bests Dold in 10th District race; Krishnamoorthi wins in 8th|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-congress-illinois-1109-20161108-story.html|accessdate=14 November 2016|publisher=The Chicago Tribune|date=November 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDold was endorsed by the [[Human Rights Campaign]], the nation's largest [[LGBT]] civil rights organization. In 2014, the organization had endorsed Schneider in his unsuccessful campaign against Dold.<ref>{{cite news|title=Morning Spin: Kirk: Trump needs me re-elected over Duckworth|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/politics/ct-mark-kirk-donald-trump-20160517-story.html|accessdate=26 May 2016|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=May 18, 2016}}</ref> Dold was also endorsed by ''The Chicago Tribune''<ref>{{cite news|title=First day of Tribune endorsements for U.S. House seats in Illinois|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-us-house-endorse-dold-schneider-edit-1010-md-20161007-story.html|accessdate=2 November 2016|publisher=The Chicago Tribune|date=October 7, 2016}}</ref> and ''The Chicago Sun-Times''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Endorsement: Bob Dold goes for the smart middle ground|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/opinion/endorsement-bob-dold-goes-for-the-smart-middle-ground/|accessdate=2 November 2016|publisher=Chicago Sun-Times|date=October 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDold, who did not endorse Republican nominee [[Donald Trump]] in the 2016 U.S. presidential election, said he would instead write in an alternative candidate's name.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Steinhauer|first1=Jennifer|title=The 5 Types of Trump-Averse Republicans|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/16/us/politics/on-donald-trump-republicans-keep-distance-in-different-ways.html?_r=0|accessdate=2 November 2016|publisher=The New York Times|date=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\n====Reputation====\nDold is a moderate Republican with a centrist voting record in Congress.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Keefe|first1=Ed|last2=Sullivan|first2=Sean|title=The Fix\u2019s top 10 House race rematches of 2014|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/01/24/the-fixs-top-10-house-race-rematches/|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=Washington Post|date=2014-01-24}}</ref><ref name=nyt>{{cite news|last1=Steinhauer|first1=Jennifer|title=2 Legislators on Tough Turf Try Delicate Run Down the Middle|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/19/us/politics/delicate-runs-for-robert-dold-and-jim-matheson.html|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=New York Times|date=2012-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Steiner|first1=Keenan|last2=Harper|first2=Jake|title=House freshmen in tight races: How many first-termers will be one-termers?|url=http://sunlightfoundation.com/blog/2012/08/21/freshmen-tight-races/|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=Sunlight Foundation|date=2012-08-21}}</ref> The non-partisan organization [[GovTrack]] has ranked Dold in the political center of Congress.<ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/spectrum.xpd ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318062631/http://www.govtrack.us/congress/spectrum.xpd |date=March 18, 2012 }}</ref> ''[[National Journal]]'' did a comprehensive study of key votes in the House, ranking  Dold as one of the most independent members of Congress.<ref>National Journal, February 25, 2012, Pages, 10\u201349</ref> Dold is an original member of the [[No Labels]] movement which, Dold stated, he hoped would help to end the gridlock in Washington, DC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robert Dold: Candidate Profile|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20120131/submitted/301319853/|accessdate=9 September 2014|publisher=Daily Herald|date=23 February 2012}}</ref> Dold is a member of the [[The Tuesday Group (United States)|Tuesday Group]], an informal caucus of moderate Republicans in the U.S. House. In 2015, Dold was elected co-chair of the Tuesday Group.<ref>{{cite news|title='Moderate' is now a dirty word for some House Republicans|url=http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20150109/NEWS02/150109833/moderate-is-now-a-dirty-word-for-some-house-republicans|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Crain's Chicago Business|date=January 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Joseph|first1=Cameron|title=Illinois Republican eyes return to Congress|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/189761-illinois-republican-eyes-return-to-congress|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=11-10-2013}}</ref> An editorial in ''The Daily Herald'' noted Dold\u2019s spirit of bipartisanship and called for more Bob Dolds in Congress.<ref>{{cite web|author=Daily Herald Editorial Board |title=Compromise not a bad word on debt|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20110728/discuss/707289677/|publisher=Daily Herald|date=July 29, 2011}}</ref> According to ''[[Roll Call]]'', Dold has moved further to the center during his second term in Congress.<ref name=cahn/> In fact, in 2015, [[The Lugar Center]], a Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit founded by former Senator [[Richard Lugar]] released a [http://www.thelugarcenter.org/ Bipartisan Index] in cooperation with Georgetown University, ranking Congressman Dold the fifth most bipartisan congressman (out of 438) in the [[114th United States Congress|114th Congress]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/ourwork-Bipartisan-Index.html | title =The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index | publisher =The Lugar Center | date =March 7, 2015 |  accessdate =June 30, 2016 | location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n====Political positions====\nDold supports abortion rights.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Quinn|title=In 10th district, first-term Republican Bob Dold tries to hold off challenger Brad Schneider|url=http://www.wbez.org/news/10th-district-first-term-republican-bob-dold-tries-hold-challenger-brad-schneider-103640|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=WBEZ|date=11-6-2012}}</ref> In 2012, Dold introduced H.R. 5650, the Protecting Women\u2019s Access to Health Care Act, which prevents lawmakers from blocking funds to [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bassett|first1=Laura|title=Bob Dold Introduces Bill To Protect Planned Parenthood Funding|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/09/bob-dold-planned-parenthood_n_1503283.html|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=Huffington Post|date=5-9-2012}}</ref> He has voiced support for stem cell research.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lissau|first1=Russell|title=10th Dist. candidates back stem cell research, oppose injunction|url=http://prev.dailyherald.com/story/?id=403285|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=Daily Herald|date=2010-08-25}}</ref>\n\nDold voted for the [[United States fiscal cliff|fiscal cliff]] compromise bill, which permanently extended most of the Bush middle class tax cuts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McClelland|first1=Edward|title=How Illinois Legislators Voted on Fiscal Cliff Bill|url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/How-Illinois-Legislators-Voted-on-Fiscal-Cliff-Bill-185408262.html|accessdate=9 September 2014|publisher=NBC Chicago|date=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe has stated his support for gay marriage and immigration reform.<ref name=eyes>{{cite news|last1=Joseph|first1=Camerson|title=Illinois Republican eyes return to Congress|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/189761-illinois-republican-eyes-return-to-congress|accessdate=9 September 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=10 November 2013}}</ref> He became the first House Republican to support the [[Equality Act of 2015|Equality Act]], which would amend the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] to include a ban on discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation or gender identity.<ref name=equality>{{cite news|title=Illinois Republican becomes first in party to back LGBT rights bill|publisher=The Hill|date=15 Jan 2016|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/266024-illinois-republican-backs-pro-lgbt-rights-bill|accessdate=15 Jan 2016}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the [[Affordable Care Act]], he has stated his desire to improve the law rather than fight to repeal or defund it.<ref name=eyes/> Dold has said the Affordable Care Act was right to require insurance coverage for pre-existing conditions and to allow students to stay on a parent's insurance to age 26.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pearson|first1=Rick|title=Dold, Schneider clash on abortion, gay marriage, health care|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-08-09/news/ct-met-illinois-10th-congressional-district-0810-20120810_1_dold-health-care-gay-marriage|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=8-9-2012}}</ref> Upon his return to the House in 2015, Dold became one of just three Republican Congressmen to vote against repeal of the Affordable Care Act - the first time any elected Republicans at the federal level voted against such a measure.<ref name=\"DH020815\">{{cite news\n | title = Dold one of three Republicans to oppose Obamacare repeal\n | work = [[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]\n | date = February 4, 2015\n | url = http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20150203/news/150209609/\n| accessdate = February 8, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nDold supports gun control measures.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Condon|first1=Stephanie|title=Bloomberg super PAC supports gun control, gay rights|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/bloomberg-super-pac-supports-gun-control-gay-rights/|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=CBS News|date=2012-10-17}}</ref> In 2015, he signed onto a bipartisan bill that would expand background checks for gun purchasers.<ref name=cahn>{{cite news|last1=Cahn|first1=Emily|title=A House Republican Moves Closer to Middle|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/bob-dold-illinois-moderate-republican/|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref> He accepts the scientific consensus on [[climate change]] and believes steps should be taken to address the issue.<ref>{{cite news|last1=James|first1=Frank|title=Green GOP Group Caught Between 'Rock And A Hard Place'|url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2014/04/22/305957364/green-gop-group-caught-between-rock-and-a-hard-place|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=NPR|date=2014-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kiely|first1=Eugene|title=Democrats Distort Vote on Climate Change|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2013/04/democrats-distort-vote-on-climate-change/|accessdate=12 September 2014|publisher=FactCheck.org|date=2013-04-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Dold introduced a bill to create a grant to expand the availability of [[naloxone]], a heroin overdose antidote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Marie|title=Dold pushes to expand availability of heroin overdose antidote|url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20160222/news/160229739/|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Daily Herald|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Personnel====\nUpon taking office in 2011, Dold hired former lobbyist Eric Burgeson, who grew up in Illinois\u2019 10th district, as his congressional [[Chief of Staff]].<ref name=rollcall20110105>{{cite news | author=Daniel Newhauser | title = Outsiders Choose Hill Professionals | publisher = [[Roll Call]] | accessdate = 2011-01-07 | date = 5 January 2011 | url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/-202126-1.html?zkMobileView=false}}</ref> Burgeson and Dold had previously worked together on Sen. [[Bob Dole]]'s 1996 presidential campaign.<ref>{{cite news | author=Kevin Bogardus | title = GOP freshman class draws K Street talent | publisher = [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | accessdate = 2011-01-07 | date = 8 December 2010 | url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/132541-gop-freshman-class-draws-talent-from-k-street-offices}}</ref> Dold instituted a policy that \"staff may not work on matters of substance with former clients.\"<ref name=rollcall20110105/> In his second term in office, his chief of staff is James Slepian.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sweet|first1=Lynn|title=Dold gets Schock's coveted Ways and Means Committee seat|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/news/7/71/542736/dold-gets-schocks-coveted-ways-means-committee-seat|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=Chicago Sun Times|date=April 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nDold was originally appointed to the Committee on Financial Services for the 114th Congress, but after the resignation of fellow Illinois Republican [[Aaron Schock]], Dold was chosen to replace him on the powerful Ways and Means Committee.<ref>[http://chicago.suntimes.com/lynn-sweet-politics/7/71/542736/dold-gets-schocks-coveted-ways-means-committee-seat Dold gets Schock's coveted Ways and Means Committee seat]</ref>\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Committee on Ways and Means]]'''\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Human Resources|Subcommittee on Human Resources]]\n**[[United States House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Social Security|Subcommittee on Social Security]]\n\n;Previous\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity|Subcommittee on Insurance, Housing and Community Opportunity]]\n\n==Personal life==\nDold is married and has three children.<ref>[http://elections.chicagotribune.com/candidate/robert-dold/ Candidate: Robert Dold], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''</ref> Dold resides in [[Kenilworth, Illinois]] and runs Rose Pest Solutions, the oldest pest control company in the country.<ref>[http://www.dailyherald.com/story/?id=320815 Kenilworth businessman to enter 10th Dist. Congressional race], Mick Zawislak, ''[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|Daily Herald]]'', September 12, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/pub/bob-dold/4/a9/987 LinkedIn Profile]. Retrieved August 18, 2010.</ref> Dold attends Kenilworth Union Church and is a scoutmaster for Kenilworth [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scout]] Troop #13.<ref name=\"suntimes-sept28\">[http://web.archive.org/web/20101003141958/http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/2755132,bob-dold-residency-issue-092810.article], Abdon M. Pallasch, ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'', September 28, 2010</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://dold.house.gov/ Congressman Bob Dold] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.doldforcongress.com/ Bob Dold for U.S. Congress]\n* {{ballotpedia|Robert_Dold|Robert Dold}}\n* {{C-SPAN|robertdold}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = D000613 | rollcall = | votesmart = 116548 | washpo = gIQA0IiWKP | ballot = Robert_J._Dold | govtrack = 412420 | opencong = 412420_Bob_Dold | c-span = robertdold | ontheissues = IL/Bob_Dold.htm | congress = robert-dold/2013 | surge = | legistorm = 2748/Rep_Robert_Dold_IL.html | fec = H0IL10302 | opensecrets = N00031103 | followthemoney = | nyt = | wsj = | worldcat = | findagrave = }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mark Kirk]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Illinois|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Illinois's 10th congressional district]]|years=2011\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brad Schneider]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brad Schneider]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Illinois|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Illinois's 10th congressional district]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-aft|after=